				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">Here's what I gathered from that wiki page:<br /><br />0x0000-0x0001 (16 bits little endian): Size of image in 8192-byte units<br />0x0002: Emulation mode<br />0x0008: Constant 0xAA<br />0x0009: Constant 0xBB<br />0x000A: 0x04 for ROM, 0x05 for WRAM<br />All other bytes are constant 0x00<br /><br /><div class="codetitle"><b>Code:</b></div><div class="codecontent">7654 3210&nbsp; Emulation mode bit meanings<br />|||| |||+- 1: Enable cartridge at banks $20-$5F and $A0-$DF during play<br />|||| ||+-- 0: run in &quot;mode 3&quot;; 1: run in &quot;mode 2&quot; (JMP Reset)<br />|||| ++--- WRAM size. 0: none; 1: 16 Kbit; 2: 64 Kbit; 3: 256 Kbit<br />|||+------ ROM uses A15. 0: LoROM (mode $20/$30); 1: HiROM (mode $21/$31)<br />||+------- WRAM mapping. 0: $7x8000-$7xFFFF; 1: $3x6000-$3x7FFF<br />||&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;(Usually matches Hi/LoROM bit)<br />|+-------- 0: Single or last file of the split game; 1: more files follow<br />+--------- 0: normal; 1: run in &quot;mode 1&quot; (JMP $8000)<br /></div><br /><br />A tool for adding the copier header can fill out bits 5 (WRAM mapping), 4 (ROM mapping), and 3-2 (WRAM size) from the internal header, and bit 6 is 0 unless you're actually using multiple floppies. But I'm so sure about what bits 7, 1, and 0 are meant for. Perhaps 0 is meant for ROM hacks that use assets from the original game?</div>

