						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">tepples wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">A tool for adding the copier header can fill out bits 5 (WRAM mapping), 4 (ROM mapping), and 3-2 (WRAM size) from the internal header, and bit 6 is 0 unless you're actually using multiple floppies. But I'm so sure about what bits 7, 1, and 0 are meant for. Perhaps 0 is meant for ROM hacks that use assets from the original game?</div><br />Bits 7 and 1 are for the memory mapping modes described in <a href="http://wiki.superfamicom.org/snes/show/Super+Wild+Card#memory_mapping_4" class="postlink">this section</a>. The bit 0 setting is described as being for modes 2 and 3 only, but the actual function is not really clear (perhaps it maps certain banks to an actual cartridge inserted in the unit instead of the image loaded from disk? The way the documentation uses the words &quot;cartridge&quot; and &quot;DRAM&quot; to describe memory mapping gives me that impression, anyway)</div>

